{"uuid":"dd25efb5-96aa-404a-981b-916fd5930740","ownerUuid":"GX3K4n8rrCSSFkacjsq6399b7tD3","description":"#### Do we have a naming convention for branches, pull requests, and commits?
_Commits_

A commit should follow this format: "issue_type: #issue_number short_issue_description" (Choose one for issue_type: feat, fix, docs, test, style, refactor).

_Branches_

Example branch naming: **MW-25/create-docs**.

_Pull requests_

The PR name should contain the issue number preceded by # and the full name of the issue. Example: **"docs: #25 add Readme.md with description of project scripts, and setup"**","isDone":false}

{"uuid":"a646f547-2be5-4dde-bc24-730293be76bc","ownerUuid":"GX3K4n8rrCSSFkacjsq6399b7tD3","description":"#### What is the development process?
- Open the issue.
- Create a branch following the naming conventions.
- Implement the feature in the newly created branch. Commit your changes.
- Merge (or pull --rebase) the changes from the main branch and resolve any conflicts.
- Create a PR to the main branch following the naming conventions. Assign reviewers from your team and share the PR link in the team chat. Address all discussions in the PR (additional changes may be required) with your team members.
- Obtain at least one approval from a team member.
- Share the link to your PR in the "PRs" chat. Continue to address any discussions in the PR until you receive a total of three approvals.
- Squash and merge the PR into the main branch.","isDone":false}

{"uuid":"fb8d447b-762c-4b74-9b18-e5a1c0b3c027","ownerUuid":"GX3K4n8rrCSSFkacjsq6399b7tD3","description":"#### What are the main entities in the application?\nThe main entities in the application are **User**, **Way**, and **DayReport**.","isDone":false}

{"uuid":"8e0a7d77-5962-41f4-b409-a2ca549f2931","ownerUuid":"GX3K4n8rrCSSFkacjsq6399b7tD3","description":"#### What layers does the application consist of, and what are their responsibilities?
The application consists of three layers: **View** layer, **DAL** layer, and **Transport** layer.

_View layer_: Responsible for displaying data and interacting with the user interface.

_DAL layer_: Responsible for data access and logic related to retrieving and processing data.

_Transport layer_: Responsible for transporting data between different parts of the application, for example, between the client and the server.","isDone":false}

{"uuid":"69241e94-0bc4-4bca-a12c-de19851c2207","ownerUuid":"GX3K4n8rrCSSFkacjsq6399b7tD3","description":"#### What conventions are adhered to in the team?
In the team, conventions are followed regarding the following development aspects:
- committing in Git
- structure and naming of folders and files
- communication
- code style (naming of constants, variables, functions, interfaces, style of importing, code commenting)","isDone":false}

{"uuid":"6556349e-63c5-4ad0-b148-a51593356d26","createdAt":1708286257148,"updatedAt":1708286257148,"description":"Ch.1.4: Myths and misconceptions about testing

Here are some myths reversed!:
- It **_is_** necessary to know about computers!
- It is **_not_** essential to be really good at programming!
- Testing is **_not_** easy.
- Testing is **_not_** heaps of routine and boredom!
- Tester should **_not_** be taught all sorts of things!
- Testers are **_not_** those who could not become programmers!
- Testing is **_not_** a difficult career to build!
- Testers are **_not always_** "at fault"!
","ownerUuid":"gaElNhls00cvmz54Ng48BexcIQz2"}

commentsStringified: {"uuid":"16e00188-2ad6-4d9e-87d1-1e770eb0ba8b","createdAt":1708286257182,"updatedAt":1708286257182,"description":"Ch.2.1.1: Software development models\n\nWaterfall, V-model: sequential, rigid; Iterative Incremental: small iterations, increased functionality; Spiral: risk-focused; Agile: adaptive, customer collaboration; each impacts testing, resources, and schedule.","ownerUuid":"gaElNhls00cvmz54Ng48BexcIQz2"}

{"uuid":"b0b56f63-98e7-4bf9-b8ef-99de5fcad96e","createdAt":1708286257182,"updatedAt":1708286257182,"description":"Ch.2.1.2: Software testing lifecyle\nThe testing lifecycle is a closed-loop sequence and follows an iterative model with stages such as general planning, acceptance criteria establishment, test strategy development, test case creation and execution, defect reporting, and results analysis and reporting. Planning and reporting are emphasized, with five of the eight stages involving project management considerations.","ownerUuid":"gaElNhls00cvmz54Ng48BexcIQz2"}

{"uuid":"e46defc5-705d-4ecc-83d2-f238e6232b8a","createdAt":1708286257193,"updatedAt":1708286257193,"description":"I will put test cases for now here:

test cases:

* Accordion

  - [ ] accordion option could be opened text visible
  - [ ] option could be closed (text hidden)
  - [ ] all options rendered
  - [ ] all options could be opened
  - [ ] all options could be opened in multiple modes
  - [ ] only one option could be opened in multiple mode


* Checkbox

  - [ ] onChange called and className changed onClick if DefaultChecked=false
  - [ ] onChange called and className changed onClick if DefaultChecked=true

* Header
  - [ ] alt text visible if source broken
  - [ ] image visible if source exists
* Input
  - [ ] placeholder visible
  - [ ] works with input mode text (some symbols are allowed and some not allowed)
  - [ ] works with input mode email (some symbols are allowed and some not allowed)
  - [ ] works with input mode number (some symbols allowed and some not allowed)
  - [ ] could not be used when disabled
  - [ ] check 'required' logic (does it work correctly)
  - [ ] check how to work when props.value and props.onChange exists at the same time
* Link
  - [ ] value rendered correctly
  - [ ] link leads to the right place
* Modal 
  - [ ] modal could be opened and closed by clicking on the grey background
  - [ ] modal could be closed by clicking on the cross
  - [ ] content rendered
* Notification
  - [ ] content rendered
  - [ ] specify what is foreground and check it works correctly
  - [ ] specify what is background and check it works correctly
* Select
  - [ ] onChange triggered if some option selected
  - [ ] selected value visible
* Sidebar
  - [ ] could be opened and closed by clicking on the grey background
  - [ ] could be closed by clicking on the cross
  - [ ] content rendered
*. Table
  - [ ] table headers rendered in the right way
  - [ ] data rendered in the right way
*. Title
  - [ ] text rendered
  - [ ] appropriate level exists on the page (check semantics)
* Tooltip
  - [ ] content rendered
  - [ ] too long content (text) hidden ","ownerUuid":"6MGYOlk90tVwng9YxCh71HdlT9E3"}

Kickstarter (Indiegogo, Selfstarter)
 * estimations, plans
 * evaluate amount we need
 * payment ?? (provide free accounts for backers)
 * collect emails (web page)
 * campaign page (like home? or landing?)
 * texts about the product
 * demo video about the product
 * kickstarter has some formal requirementes, we should be prepared

Product hunt
 * We can launch on each significant product iteration (not often than 6 month)
 * usually +1000 traffic, #1 ~ 10_000 extra traffcic (10% leads)
 * we should optimize our funels for capturing emails before launching
 * we firstly should prelaunch audience (has a small following)
 * it is not a channel for creating the first set of users (they recommend to have ~400 people audience before starting)
 * probably launch is better on Tuesday-thursday

 Payments (online payment solution vs bank aquiring)
 * for working business ~ week to connect
 * lets focus on payment services, it is easier to connect
 * stripe (I like it), paypal
